Geographic Spread

# Remove rows with missing coordinates
sites_sf <- mags %>%
  distinct(site_ID, decimalLatitude, decimalLongitude) %>%
  filter(!is.na(decimalLatitude), !is.na(decimalLongitude)) %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("decimalLongitude","decimalLatitude"), crs = 4326)

# Summarize diversity per site
site_summary <- mags %>%
  group_by(site_ID) %>%
  summarize(mean_pH = mean(soilInWaterpH, na.rm = TRUE),
            richness = n_distinct(bin_id))

# Join summaries to spatial data
sites_sf <- sites_sf %>%
  left_join(site_summary, by = "site_ID")

# Map sites colored by mean soil pH
ggplot(sites_sf) +
  geom_sf(aes(color = mean_pH), size = 3) +
  scale_color_viridis_c() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "NEON Sites Colored by Mean Soil pH")

Community Ecology Approaches

Alpha diversity

Alpha diversity is the mean species diversity at a local scale accounting for the number of species present (richness) and their abundance (evenness) in the area. In the CoPilot-generated analysis, Shannon diversty and Pielouâs evenness are used.

Shannon index is a method of calculating diversity using species evenness and richness where higher values equal greater diversity.

Pielouâs evenness exclusively focuses on evenness and the distribution of species in an area.

library(vegan)
# Richness: number of unique MAGs per site
alpha_div <- mags %>%
  group_by(site_ID) %>%
  summarize(richness = n_distinct(bin_id))

# Evenness: using Shannon index
# First build site x MAG abundance matrix
comm_matrix <- mags %>%
  count(site_ID, bin_id) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = bin_id, values_from = n, values_fill = 0)

# Extract abundance data
abund <- comm_matrix %>% select(-site_ID)

# Shannon diversity and Pielou's evenness
shannon <- diversity(abund, index = "shannon")
richness <- specnumber(abund)
evenness <- shannon / log(richness)

alpha_results <- tibble(
  site_ID = comm_matrix$site_ID,
  richness = richness,
  shannon = shannon,
  evenness = evenness
)

alpha_results

Beta diversity

Beta diversity is the variation in species diversity between two separate areas. The CoPilot analysis uses NMDS, CAP, and PERMANOVA to examine this.

NMDS (Non-metric Multidimensional Scaling) is an unconstrained ordination method used to arrange sites based on their dissimilarities.

CAP (Canonical Analysis of Principal Coordinates) is a constrained ordination method that tests how much community variation is explained by environmental gradients.

PERMANOVA (Permutational Multivariate Analysis of Variance) is a test used to show differences in community composition among groups.

Step 1: Prepare the community matrix
library(tidyverse)

# Drop rows with missing site_ID or bin_id
comm_matrix <- mags %>%
  filter(!is.na(site_ID), !is.na(bin_id)) %>%
  count(site_ID, bin_id) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = bin_id, values_from = n, values_fill = 0)

# Extract abundance data
abund <- comm_matrix %>% select(-site_ID)

# Assign row names safely
rownames(abund) <- comm_matrix$site_ID
Step 2: Prepare environmental data
env_data <- mags %>%
  group_by(site_ID) %>%
  summarize(
    soilMoisture = mean(soilMoisture, na.rm = TRUE),
    soilTemp = mean(soilTemp, na.rm = TRUE),
    soilInWaterpH = mean(soilInWaterpH, na.rm = TRUE),
    soilInCaClpH = mean(soilInCaClpH, na.rm = TRUE),
    elevation = mean(elevation, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

env_data <- env_data %>% filter(site_ID %in% rownames(abund))
env_data <- env_data[match(rownames(abund), env_data$site_ID), ]
Step 3: NMDS (unconstrained coordination)
set.seed(123)
nmds <- metaMDS(abund, distance = "bray", k = 2, trymax = 100)

PERMANOVA

PERMANOVA assesses significance using permutations (ordered arrangements) of variation components that are explained by residuals or predictors.

Step 1: Prepare the community matrix
library(tidyverse)
library(vegan)

# Build site x MAG abundance matrix
comm_matrix <- mags %>%
  filter(!is.na(site_ID), !is.na(bin_id)) %>%
  count(site_ID, bin_id) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = bin_id, values_from = n, values_fill = 0)

# Extract abundance data
abund <- comm_matrix %>% select(-site_ID)
rownames(abund) <- comm_matrix$site_ID
Step 2: Prepare environmental data
env_data <- mags %>%
  group_by(site_ID) %>%
  summarize(
    soilMoisture = mean(soilMoisture, na.rm = TRUE),
    soilTemp = mean(soilTemp, na.rm = TRUE),
    soilInWaterpH = mean(soilInWaterpH, na.rm = TRUE),
    soilInCaClpH = mean(soilInCaClpH, na.rm = TRUE),
    elevation = mean(elevation, na.rm = TRUE),
    latitude = mean(decimalLatitude, na.rm = TRUE),
    longitude = mean(decimalLongitude, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

# Align order with abundance matrix
env_data <- env_data %>%
  filter(site_ID %in% rownames(abund)) %>%
  arrange(match(site_ID, rownames(abund)))
Step 3: Run PERMANOVA
# Test soil chemistry + geography effects
adonis_results <- adonis2(
  abund ~ soilMoisture + soilTemp + soilInWaterpH + soilInCaClpH + elevation + latitude + longitude,
  data = env_data,
  method = "bray",
  permutations = 999
)

Step 4: Interpret results
Pr(>F) = 1 shows that the model is not statistically significant, meaning the predictors do not explain community variation in the MAG data better than random chance. The R-squared model is 0.269, meaning about 26.9% of the variation in MAG community composition is explained by environmental variables, but the others are unexplained.
